definition.value: A person who has suffered from any of various forms of child sexual abuse.
Any of various human rights movements which advocate for squatters' rights.
Any of various human rights movements which advocate for workers' rights.
The (usually marital) partner of someone's parent, and not their biological or adoptive parent.
The process by which an individual or group becomes stigmatized.
A name of a place.
A name of a geographical feature on the planet Earth.
Narrowly, a name of an urban element; broadly, the name of an element which is anthropogenic in nature.
A name of a street or road element.
A marriage in which participants are from different cultural backgrounds.
A theory which claims scientific merit, but is not scientific in nature, usually (but not always) with an underlying agenda.
Pseudoscientific theories claiming to fall under the scope of the field of biology.
Any of various theories which claim to be scientific, but instead push a racist agenda.

A scientific racist theory, first proposed by Canadian psychologist J. Philippe Rushton in 1985, which attempts to apply r/K selection theory to human races. According to Rushton, this theory explains race differences in fertility, IQ, criminality, and sexual anatomy and behavior. The theory also hypothesizes that a single factor, the "K factor", affects multiple population statistics Rushton referred to as "life-history traits".

Many researchers have criticized Rushton's theory. It has been argued that the predictions based on the theory "are supported by selective citation and misrepresentation of the research literature and by the use of unreliable sources" and that Rushton's methodology "indicates a lack of familiarity with ecological thinking and scientific method in general." A 2014 study found differences in the General Factor of Personality across races that were not compatible with differential K theory.

A scientific racist theory, named after educational psychologist Arthur Jensen, which was originally defined as "the theory that IQ is largely determined by the genes". However, because Jensen and proponents often used this theory to argue scientifically racist thought, it became associated with the theory that Black persons are genetically mentally inferior to white persons, based on the results of IQ tests.

Contemporary scientific consensus has shown that genetic factors do not  explain IQ differences between socially constructed racial groups. Despite this, a number of prominent evolutionary psychologists still preach Jensenism under other labels such as "race realism" or "human biodiversity". For instance, The Bell Curve, by Richard Herrnstein and Charles Murray claimed to support Jensenism. It is also notable that a number of far-right and alt-right scholars and organizations continue to fuel Jensenist beliefs in the 21st century. One such organization, the Pioneer Fund, deemed a hate group by the Southern Poverty Law Center, attempted to fund distribution of a Nazi propaganda film about eugenics in U.S. schools and churches. Generally, Jensenism is highly associated with the 21st century "intellectual dark web" of scholars, many of whom have espoused sexist, racist, homophobic, and transphobic beliefs.

A white supremacist ideology which views the supposed Aryan race as a distinct and superior racial group which is entitled to rule the rest of humanity. Initially promoted by racist theorists such as Arthur de Gobineau and Houston Stewart Chamberlain, Aryanism reached its peak of influence in Nazi Germany. In the 1930s and 40s, the regime applied the ideology with full force, sparking World War II with the 1939 invasion of Poland in pursuit of Lebensraum, or living space, for the Aryan people. The racial policies which were implemented by the Nazis during the 1930s came to a head during their conquest of Europe and the Soviet Union, culminating in the industrial mass murder of six million Jews and eleven million other victims in what is now known as the Holocaust.
A racist and white supremacist ideology which views the "Nordic race" as an endangered and superior racial group.

The notion of the superiority of the "Nordic race" and the superiority of the Northwestern European nations that were associated with this supposed race influenced the United States' Immigration Act of 1924 (which effectively banned or severely limited the immigration of Italians, Jews, and other Southern and Eastern Europeans) and the later Immigration and Nationality Act of 1952, and it was also present in other countries outside Northwestern Europe and the United States, such as Australia, Canada, and South Africa. By the 1930s, the Nazis claimed that the Nordic race was the most superior branch of the "Aryan race" and constituted a master race (Herrenvolk). The full application of this belief system—the invasion of Poland and further conquest in the pursuit of Lebensraum, 'living space'—was the immediate catalyst for World War II and led directly to the industrial mass murder of six million Jews and eleven million other victims in what is now known as the Holocaust.

A subtype of degeneration theory which posited that racial desegregation, the abolition of slavery, racial equality and equity, racial civil rights, and other societal changes were somehow connected to societal collapse.

A subtype of degeneration theory which posited that changing sexual or gender norms, homosexuality, "sexual inversion", transness, gender equality, feminism, BDSM, etc., were somehow leading to the collapse of society.

The very idea of "sexual degeneracy" has been stretched to inane conclusions, with those in the 19th and 20th believing that allowing women to vote would even constitute the collapse of society, or that homosexuality had something to do with the collapse of the Roman Empire, which is demonstrably false. However, despite such theories being bizarre, they are still published commonly in the 21st century. For instance, The Guardian published an article "How same-sex marriage could ruin civilisation" in 2015. A 2011 Telegraph article claimed that the "Fall of the Roman Empire caused by 'contagion of homosexuality'". And, in 2022, Jordan Peterson claimed that transgender people were somehow evidence of societal collapse.

Any of various theories which utilize race as a proxy for other characteristics. For instance, calling race a social determinant of health, rather than racism, the actual underlying social determinant. The usage of race corrections in health care and "race-norming" could also be considered forms of race proxy theory. However, the original usage of the phrase "race proxy theory" was to describe how white people often use neighborhood racial composition as a proxy for various "social problems" (such as crime).

Any of various theories which utilize race as a proxy to "correct" or "adjust" some value. Theories of race correction have been utilized widely in health care, and have also been used to adjust test scores. Both practices have been connected with and compared to eugenics and pseudoscientific racism, because the supposed proxy related to these changes is unclear at best, and unduely malicious at worst.

Any of various pseudoscientific movements which purport that masking does not help prevent the spread of disease, or are some sort of conspiracy-related government plot, among other inane explanations. Anti-mask movements gained traction alongside anti-vaccination movements during the COVID-19 pandemic.
In vitro fertilization with subsequent transfer to an unrelated surrogate.

label.value: in vitro fertilization with intracytoplasmic sperm injection

definition.value: An in vitro fertilization (IVF) procedure in which a single sperm cell is injected directly into the cytoplasm of an egg. This technique is used in order to prepare the gametes for the obtention of embryos that may be transferred to a maternal uterus. With this method, the acrosome reaction is skipped.
An arrangement, often supported by a legal agreement, whereby a woman (the gestational carrier) agrees to bear a child for another person or people, who will become the child's parent(s) after birth.
A process where one person, who did not provide the egg used in conception, carries a fetus through pregnancy and gives birth to a baby for another person or couple.

Surrogacy in which a surrogate agrees to be artificially inseminated with sperm of a biological father, to gestate the fetus, and then, after birth, the surrogacy is terminated and the surrogate gives up her parental rights in favor of the intending parent or parents.
The practice of traveling to another country or jurisdiction for fertility treatment, which is regarded as a form of medical tourism.
A type of book censorship in which bans of particular materials are passed by various cultural, religious, legal, or educational bodies.
A type of book censorship which involves deliberate destruction by fire of books or other written materials, usually carried out in a public context.
A systematic form of book censorship in which particular types of materials are removed from public or private book repositories.
Systematic book censorship in which LGBTQIA+-related materials are removed from public or private book repositories.
Any of various book burnings involving LGBTQIA+-related materials.
Any of various book bannings involving LGBTQIA+-related materials.
Radical feminist ideologies based upon inclusionary or exclusionary activity criteria.
Radical feminist ideologies based upon exclusionary activity criteria regarding sex work and sex workers.

A critical term for types of feminism that advocate for enhancing and increasing prison sentences that deal with feminist and gender issues. It is the belief that harsher and longer prison sentences will help work towards solving these issues. The phrase "carceral feminism" was coined by feminist sociologist Elizabeth Bernstein in her 2007 article, "The Sexual Politics of the 'New Abolitionism'". Examining the contemporary anti-trafficking movement in the United States, Bernstein introduced the term to describe a type of feminist activism which casts all forms of sexual labor as sex-trafficking.

A political movement that advocates replacing policing with other systems of public safety. Police abolitionists believe that policing, as a system, is inherently flawed and cannot be reformed—a view that rejects the ideology of police reformists. While reformists seek to address the ways in which policing occurs, abolitionists seek to transform policing altogether through a process of disbanding, disempowering, and disarming the police. Abolitionists argue that the institution of policing is deeply rooted in a history of white supremacy and settler colonialism and that it is inseparable from a pre-existing racial capitalist order, and thus believe a reformist approach to policing will always fail.
A birth certificate provided shortly after birth for a newborn.

label.value: birth certificate after gender marker change

An amended birth certificate which replaces an original birth certificate after a court-ordered (or other legal) name change.
An inventory which assesses an individual's knowledge in some specific area or areas.
An inventory which assesses an individual's knowledge in some specific area or areas of sexuality, sexual health, or other sexual knowledge.
A sexual non-identity, in which an individual denies any specific label related to their sexual identity.
A person who identifies as pomosexual; i.e. an individual who does not wish to label their sexual orientation or sexuality generally.
A sexuality defined by its lack of relationship to labels, defined by its avoidance of labels, or as its not fitting with any other specific labels.
